Mixed Effects Models Simulations

  • Simulation of a single dataset
  • Monte Carlo Simulation to assess possible bias of estimates
  • Increasing the cluster size

Robert Long: 27 June 2021

Flexibly simulating data for a mixed effects model with random intercepts and random slopes for a numeric variable including the correlation between slopes and intercepts.

I have been using the following code, and variations on it for a number of years in my own research, and to help me answer questions on CrossValidated related to mixed models. Here is a link to all the mixed model questions I have answered there.

We will work with a dataset consisting of a single explanatory variable X, and a grouping variable G. There are several ways we can set this up, but for simplicity, initially we will deal with balanced groups containing a fixed number of values for X. Later we will relax this to handle unbalanced groups as well as randomly generated values for X, and more complex models generally.

We will work with the general formula for mixed effects models:

Y=Xβ+Zu+ϵY=Xβ+Zu+ϵ
where XX is the n×pn×p model matrix for the fixed effects, ββ is the p×1p×1 fixed effects coefficient vector, ZZ is the n×qn×q model matrix for the qq-dimensional vector-valued random-effects variable uu, and ϵϵ is the error term vector.

Simulation of a single dataset

n_group <- 6

dt <- expand.grid(G = 1:n_group, X = 1:5)

Here we are forming the dataframe we will use.

Now we create the model matrix for the fixed effects

X <- model.matrix( ~ X, data = dt)

For the model matrix for the random effects, Z, there are a few ways we can approach this, but the easiest is to make use of the lFormula function in lme4. To do this we need to add the outcome variable Y to the dataframe, but since we haven’t yet simulated it, we will just use a column of 1s since this will not affect Z in any way:

library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
dt$Y <- 1
myFormula <- 'Y ~ X + (X | G)'

foo <- lFormula(eval(myFormula), dt)
Z <- t(as.matrix(foo$reTrms$Zt))

Now we set the remaining parameters for the simulation: the fixed effects (betas), random effects standard deviations (s1 and s2), the residual standard error (eps) and the correlation between these, rho:

betas <- c(1, 1) # Fixed effects parameters

s1 <- 2   #  SD of random intercepts
s2 <- 1   #  SD of random slopes

eps <- 1  # SD of residual error

rho <- -0.9  # correlation between intercepts and slopes

Next we form the variance-covariance matrix we will use to simulate the random effects:

cormat <-  matrix(c(s1, rho, rho, s2), 2, 2)  # correlation matrix 
covmat <- sdcor2cov(cormat)                   # covariance matrix (needed for mvrnorm)

Then we simulate the random effects, and the residual error:

set.seed(1)

umat <- MASS::mvrnorm(n_group, c(0, 0), covmat, empirical = TRUE)  # simulate the random effects
  
u <- c(rbind(umat[, 1], umat[, 2]))  # lme4 needs the random effects in this order (interleaved)
  
e <- rnorm(nrow(dt), 0, eps)   # residual error

Note that I have used set.seed() in this block, since it occurs just before the first simulation. It is good practice to set.seed() at the top of a source file, but we will extend this code later where we use Monte-Carlo simulation and for that we would like to set a different seed for each simulation at this point.

Finally we can compute the simulated value for Y using the general mixed model equation above:

dt$Y <- X %*% betas + Z %*% u + e   

m0 <- lmer(myFormula, dt) 
summary(m0)  
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: Y ~ X + (X | G)
##    Data: dt
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 103.9
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.1003 -0.4614  0.2525  0.6513  1.2274 
## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev. Corr 
##  G        (Intercept) 4.6219   2.1499        
##           X           1.0061   1.0031   -0.95
##  Residual             0.9125   0.9553        
## Number of obs: 30, groups:  G, 6
## 
## Fixed effects:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value
## (Intercept)   0.8895     0.9683   0.919
## X             1.0373     0.4277   2.425
## 
## Correlation of Fixed Effects:
##   (Intr)
## X -0.931

In this case we see that we can recover all the parameters well:

  • residual standard deviation is estimated as 0.9553 vs 1.0 simulated
  • standard deviation for the random intercept: 2.1499 vs 2.0
  • standard deviation for the random slopes: 1.0031 vs 1.0
  • correlation between slopes and intercepts: -0.95 vs -0.9
  • fixed effects of 0.8895 and 1.0373 vs 1.0 and 1.0 respectively

Of course, these are not exactly correct, and we would never expect them to be. One major area of interest is whether the estimates are unbiased, and to investigate this we can use Monte-Carlo simulation

Monte Carlo Simulation to assess possible bias of estimates

The approach is as follows:

  • set all variables and parameters for the simulation
  • declare and assign storage for vectors which will hold the parameter estimates for each simulation
  • we will run n_sim simulations
  • we loop n_sim times, each time setting a unique seed
  • we need to check that the model has converged and that it has non converged to a singular fit. For this we will use the following little helper function:
hasConverged <- function (mm) {
  
  if ( !(class(mm)[1] == 'lmerMod' | class(mm)[1] == 'lmerModLmerTest'))  stop('Error must pass a lmerMod object')
  
  retval <- NULL
  
  if(is.null(unlist(mm@optinfo$conv$lme4))) {
    retval = 1
  }
  else {
    if (isSingular(mm)) {
      retval = 0
    } else {
      retval = -1
    }
  }
  return(retval)
}

This function returns 1 if the model has converged (not to a singular fit).

Note that, the code that follows is essentially the same as the code above with the addition of the loop and the vectors used for saving the estimates.

n_group <- 6

dt <- expand.grid(G = 1:n_group, X = 1:5)

X <- model.matrix( ~ X, data = dt)

dt$Y <- 1
myFormula <- 'Y ~ X + (X | G)'

foo <- lFormula(eval(myFormula), dt)
Z <- t(as.matrix(foo$reTrms$Zt))

betas <- c(1, 1) # Fixed effects parameters

s1 <- 2   #  SD of random intercepts
s2 <- 1   #  SD of random slopes

eps <- 1  # SD of residual error

rho <- -0.9  # correlation between intercepts and slopes
cormat <-  matrix(c(s1, rho, rho, s2), 2, 2) 
covmat <- sdcor2cov(cormat) # this function is from lme4

n_sim <- 100 
vec_s1 <- vec_s2 <- vec_eps <- vec_rho <- vec_fe1 <- vec_fe2 <- numeric(n_sim)
vec_s1 <- vec_s2 <- vec_eps <- vec_rho <- vec_fe1 <- vec_fe2 <- rep(NA, n_sim)

for (i in 1:n_sim) {
  set.seed(i)

  umat <- MASS::mvrnorm(n_group, c(0, 0), covmat, empirical = TRUE)  

  u <- c(rbind(umat[, 1], umat[, 2])) 

  e <- rnorm(nrow(dt), 0, eps)

  dt$Y <- X %*% betas + Z %*% u + e   

  m0 <- lmer(myFormula, dt) 
  
  tmp_dt <- data.frame(VarCorr(m0))
  
  if (hasConverged(m0) == 1) {
    vec_s1[i] <- tmp_dt[1,5]
    vec_s2[i] <- tmp_dt[2,5]
    vec_rho[i] <- tmp_dt[3,5]                     
    vec_eps[i] <- tmp_dt[4,5] 
    vec_fe1[i] <- coef(summary(m0))[1]
    vec_fe2[i] <- coef(summary(m0))[2]
  }
}  
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## Warning in checkConv(attr(opt, "derivs"), opt$par, ctrl = control$checkConv, :
## Model failed to converge with max|grad| = 0.0318009 (tol = 0.002, component 1)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular

So we see from the output above that there were 6 singular fits and 1 non-convergence. So we should expect to find 7 NAs in the simulation vectors:

sum(is.na(vec_s1))
## [1] 7

and indeed we do

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data.frame(vec_s1), aes(x = vec_s1)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 ) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept = s1), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_s1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 2.039515

So we find that the estimate is unbiased. The mean of the simulations is 2.04 and the actual value used to create the simulations was 2, and we have plotted a vertical line on the histogram to show this. We can now follow the same procedures for the other estimates:

ggplot(data.frame(vec_s2), aes(x = vec_s2)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 ) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept = s2), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_s2, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.012603
ggplot(data.frame(vec_rho), aes(x = vec_rho)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = rho), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_rho, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] -0.9036961
ggplot(data.frame(vec_eps), aes(x = vec_eps)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = eps), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_eps, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9732599
ggplot(data.frame(vec_fe1), aes(x = vec_fe1)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = betas[1]), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_fe1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9964722
ggplot(data.frame(vec_fe2), aes(x = vec_fe2)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = betas[2]), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_fe2, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9947593

So we find that all the estimates are unbiased. The main point of concern is that there is quite a wide spread of estimates. This is likely due, at least in part to the small number of clusters.

Increasing the cluster size

If we change

n_group <- 6

to

n_group <- 100

and re-run the simulations, then we obtain:

ggplot(data.frame(vec_s1), aes(x = vec_s1)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 ) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept = s1), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_s1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 2.00038
ggplot(data.frame(vec_s2), aes(x = vec_s2)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 ) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept = s2), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_s1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 2.00038
ggplot(data.frame(vec_rho), aes(x = vec_rho)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = rho), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_rho, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] -0.8994075
ggplot(data.frame(vec_eps), aes(x = vec_eps)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = eps), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_eps, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.001352
ggplot(data.frame(vec_fe1), aes(x = vec_fe1)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = betas[1]), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_fe1, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.9979048
ggplot(data.frame(vec_fe2), aes(x = vec_fe2)) + geom_histogram(colour = 'blue', fill = 'grey', bins = 20 )+ geom_vline(aes(xintercept = betas[2]), colour =  'black')

mean(vec_fe2, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.999136

We can see from the above that the estimates are much better behaved with a larger number of clusters.
